Parking in Eindhoven, Data Analysis & Investigation¶

The city of Eindhoven has tons of available data. This is mostly comprised of geographic point locations combined with various other domains. This data by itself can provide some interesting insights into the city and its surroundings.

What is even more interesting that new 'hidden' information is uncovered when combining some of these domains.

In the upcoming sections the parking data will be analyzed, treated and displayed. The dataset contains the following:

  • ID - Id of the object
  • STREET - Street name
  • TYPE - Type of parking spot (6 unique)
  • COUNT - Number of available parking spots
  • LON - Longitudinal coordinates
  • LAT - Latitudal coordinates
  • GEO_2D - Geolocation in 2D

The goal is to analyze the data and describe what steps are needed to succesfully recreate a scatter plot of parking spots from the city of Eindhoven.

Next to that a look will be taken at a different approach of importing data. (not csv dump but web api)

And finally ready the prepared dataset with a storage solution that can be used for ML algorithms.

Importing the dataset¶

Firstly the dataset and standard libraries which are used frequently have to be imported.

De delimiter of the dataset is';' in this situation. This can be seen by opening the dataset.

The top datapoint from the dataset has been removed because it contained column information

Treating the dataset¶

From the composition of the dataset we deduced there are 175 different streets, and over 11k parking spots. It would be a difficult task to plot all 11k points.

We will take each street as a single point, and the weight will be dependent on the count of parking spots in that street.

Lets see the count of each street.

In [5]:
dataset['STREET'].value_counts()

We can see that there is one street which is a little suspicious. 'Niet ingevuld' means that this field has not been filled in.

These datapoints will be removed from the dataset for now. Later on they will be plotted individually with a different color of representation compared to the streets.

In [6]:
unknown_street_parking = [d for d in dataset['STREET'] if d == 'Niet ingevuld']

#pandas.Dateframe.isin will return boolean values depending on whether 
#each element is inside the list a or not. You then invert this with 
#the ~ to convert True to False and vice versa.
dataset = dataset[~dataset['STREET'].isin(unknown_street_parking)]
        
street_count = dataset['STREET'].value_counts()
street_count.head()
Out[6]:

Now that we have the parking count of each street. we can apply this later to the coordinates of each street.

To calculate the mean coordinates of each street the dataset will be grouped and a mean will be determined.

By opening the dataset in Excel I noticed that the structure was a little off. So lets check the type of LON and LAT, If we want to perform calculations on these they should be either a float or int.

In [7]:
type(dataset['LON'][1])
Out[7]:
str

The type of LON and LAT is a string. It has to be converted to a float first. Also the decimal has to be replaced by a point.

In [8]:
dataset['LON'] = dataset['LON'].str.replace(',', '.').astype(float)
dataset['LAT'] = dataset['LAT'].str.replace(',', '.').astype(float)
dataset.head()

For now we are only interested in few columns. Namely: STREET, LON, LAT and the total count of grouped streets which we will cal TOTAL.

The rest will be dropped from the table. And a mean will be calculated for both the LON and LAT coordinates.

In [9]:
combo_arr = dataset.drop(['TYPE', 'COUNT', 'GEO_2D', 'ID'], axis=1)
        
grouped_combo = combo_arr.groupby(['STREET']).mean()
grouped_combo['pointCount'] = street_count
grouped_combo

Conclusion¶

As we can see from the images above data representation plays a very important role. It has to be correct, but it also has to be displayed in an understandable manner.

By only displaying the scatter plot you get a rough idea of where the hot-spots are located. But you cannot place it very well because there is no location to correlate to through sight.

By implementing a map things become more clear. The only problem was that I could not figure out how to apply concentration on the points. This is deceiving because it looks like all points are equal.

When displaying the final map with all points from the original dataset we can see the actual concentration. Which differs from both the scatter plot and grouped plots on the map.

By creating different angles of approach to a certain situation the total picture renders clearer. Story-telling plays an important role in data analysis.

Dataset from web api¶

An import from an external website is an api call with a specific route.

Importing packages¶

The panda package has already been imported. To make an HTTP request we need another package:

In [12]:
import requests

This package will help us communicate between the local browser and web server.

GET request from endpoint¶

The next will be making the GET request to the endpoint. To do this we will need a target URL.

In [13]:
#url = 'https://data.eindhoven.nl/api/records/1.0/search/?dataset=meldingen-openbare-ruimte&q=&rows=10000&refine.onderwerp=7.1+Parkeeroverlast'
#url = 'https://data.eindhoven.nl/api/records/1.0/search/?dataset=meldingen-openbare-ruimte&q=&rows=10000&sort=aangemaakt&facet=nummer&facet=gebied&facet=onderwerp&facet=aangemaakt&facet=gewijzigd&facet=buurt&facet=locatie_ter_hoogte_van&facet=wijkcode&facet=stadsdeelcode_&facet=wijknaam&facet=stadsdeelnaam'
url = 'https://data.eindhoven.nl/api/records/1.0/search/?dataset=parkeerplaatsen&q=&rows=1000&facet=straat&facet=type_en_merk&facet=aantal'

We will use the requests library to make a GET request

In [14]:
r = requests.get(url)
r
Out[14]:
<Response [200]>

A status code 200 means that the requests has been succesful!

Extracting data¶

Now the data will be extracted using the Json method.

In [34]:
json = r.json()

Conclusion¶

Treating a dataset so that it can be interpreted and displaying the results in a graph. In addition to that importing a dataset through different means other than a csv dump to get comparable data.

From previous exercises I got some experience in treating and preparing data. I applied the same techniques. I added extra explanations before each code block so that me and the reader are satisfied with the flow and clarity of the notebook. Working with world-map data was a first, as well as importing data through a web-api. I used a lot of sources and translated the information into my own words for better understanding.

One of the most important skills I got to practice with during this exercise is visual story telling using data. It is of great importance to not only treat and clean data. But also to give it a nice representation so that connections or irregularities. can be seen. Secondly I also got to train with importing data from an external web-api. In theory I would be able to make my own API's now and import them for further analysis.

The only difference I would make is to markdown my though process. Even when trying out new pieces of code. In my opinion the code was tried out, but didnt succeed should be left there with an explanation as to why it did not live up to the standards. In this way the thoughtprocess is even more established in the notebook.
